Note:
WebAssembly (WAT) Translation Round-Trip Probe

End-to-end proof that the WebAssembly text-format (WAT) translation pipeline is
REAL, not a skeleton:

    WAT s-expression source
      -> wasm_lexer       (tokenize: parens, $identifiers, "strings", numbers,
                           keywords (module/func/param/result/local/export/...),
                           value types (i32/i64/f32/f64), instruction mnemonics)
      -> wasm_parser      (recursive-descent s-expression tree; each head keyword
                           is classified into a WasmNode tag - WASM_FUNCTION,
                           WASM_PARAM, WASM_RESULT, WASM_LOCAL, WASM_IMPORT,
                           WASM_EXPORT, WASM_TYPE, or WASM_INSTRUCTION)
      -> wasm_to_hir      (partition the module tree into a HIR dictionary with
                           "functions"/"imports"/"exports"/"types" lists; each
                           function is a dictionary with "parameters"/"results"/
                           "locals"/"body" lists; each body instruction is a
                           dictionary keyed by "opcode" plus an "operands" list of
                           nested instruction / immediate-operand dictionaries)
      -> hir_to_wasm      (emit the HIR dictionary back to canonical WAT text)

The HIR model is the dictionary/list-literal model (String-keyed dictionaries),
NOT the typed hir.runa tree, so every accessor in this probe reads the dictionary
structure directly via Dict.get / List.get / List.size.

The probe feeds a representative WAT snippet:

    (module
      (func $add (param $a i32) (param $b i32) (result i32)
        (i32.add (local.get $a) (local.get $b)))
      (export "add" (func $add)))

exercising: a (module ...) root, a named (func $add ...) with two named+typed
params, a (result i32), a folded body instruction (i32.add ...) whose two
operands are themselves nested (local.get $a) / (local.get $b) instructions, and
an (export "add" (func $add)).

It then:
  1. Drives the source through lexer -> parser -> to_hir and asserts the HIR
     dictionary type tag and the top-level section counts.
  2. Asserts the lowered function name, its parameter names and types, its result
     type, and the body instruction's opcode plus the opcodes / immediates of its
     nested operands survived on the FIRST emission's HIR. Asserts the export
     name and internal reference.
  3. Emits the HIR back to WAT text and asserts the text is non-empty.
  4. Re-parses the emitted text back into HIR (the SECOND emission) and asserts
     the two HIR streams are STRUCTURALLY EQUAL via recursive comparators: same
     function count, same per-function name / parameter stream / result stream /
     body instruction tree (opcode + operand arity + operand kind + nested
     opcodes and immediate values at every position), and same export stream
     (name + internal_name). The backend canonicalises whitespace and the folded
     export form, so the byte stream differs while the meaning is identical;
     structural equality is the correct fidelity check.

Exit code: number of failed assertions (0 == all passed). No exit_with_code.
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/wasm/wasm_lexer.runa" as WasmLexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/wasm/wasm_parser.runa" as WasmParser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/wasm/wasm_to_hir.runa" as WasmFrontend
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/wasm/hir_to_wasm.runa" as WasmBackend
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "tests/test_utils.runa" as TestUtils

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Pipeline driver: WAT source -> HIR dictionary
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The WAT pipeline has no single source-to-HIR convenience, so the probe owns the
chain explicitly: create_lexer wraps the source, tokenize fills the lexer's token
list, create_parser snapshots that list, parse builds the s-expression AST, and
translate_wasm_to_hir partitions the AST into the HIR dictionary. Returning the
dictionary pointer (or 0 on any stage failure) lets the caller assert on one
value.
@End Reasoning
Process called "wasm_source_to_hir" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from WasmLexer with source
    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc tokenize from WasmLexer with lexer

    Let parser be proc create_parser from WasmParser with lexer
    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ast be proc parse from WasmParser with parser
    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let hir be proc translate_wasm_to_hir from WasmFrontend with ast
    Return hir
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HIR accessors (mirror the backend's dictionary read contract)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The HIR dictionary keys are content-hashed Strings, so a fresh literal key
constructed here resolves to the same entry the frontend stored under. This
helper builds the key and fetches the value (section list or scalar) so the
comparators and assertions can read it uniformly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "dict_get" takes node as Integer, key as String returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let key_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with key
    Return proc get from Dict with node, key_str
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the number of entries in a list, tolerating a missing (0) list so the
count assertions read uniformly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "list_count" takes lst as Integer returns Integer:
    If lst is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc size from List with lst
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns entry i of a list as a raw pointer so callers can read its fields.
@End Reasoning
Process called "list_at" takes lst as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    If lst is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc get from List with lst, index
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Structural equality of two instruction trees (recursive)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Two body instructions are equal when their opcodes match and their operand lists
match position-for-position. An operand is either a nested instruction (compared
recursively) or a simple immediate (compared by its "value" payload). Comparing
the opcode, the operand arity, the operand kind at each position, and recursing
into nested instructions proves operand-level round-trip fidelity for folded WAT
expression trees without being fooled by the backend's canonical re-rendering.
@End Reasoning
Process called "instructions_equal" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let opcode_a be proc dict_get with a, "opcode"
    Let opcode_b be proc dict_get with b, "opcode"
    Let opcodes_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with opcode_a, opcode_b
    If opcodes_match is not equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ops_a be proc dict_get with a, "operands"
    Let ops_b be proc dict_get with b, "operands"
    Let opc_a be proc list_count with ops_a
    Let opc_b be proc list_count with ops_b
    If opc_a is not equal to opc_b:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than opc_a:
        Let op_a be proc list_at with ops_a, i
        Let op_b be proc list_at with ops_b, i

        Let type_a be proc dict_get with op_a, "type"
        Let type_b be proc dict_get with op_b, "type"
        Let types_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with type_a, type_b
        If types_match is not equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: An operand tagged "instruction" is a nested folded instruction;
        Note: recurse. Any other operand is a simple immediate compared by value.
        Let is_nested be proc string_equals from StringCore with type_a, "instruction"
        If is_nested is equal to 1:
            Let nested_match be proc instructions_equal with op_a, op_b
            If nested_match is not equal to 1:
                Return 0
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Let val_a be proc dict_get with op_a, "value"
            Let val_b be proc dict_get with op_b, "value"
            Let vals_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with val_a, val_b
            If vals_match is not equal to 1:
                Return 0
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Two body instruction streams are equal when they have the same length and
structurally equal instructions at every position.
@End Reasoning
Process called "body_streams_equal" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    Let count_a be proc list_count with a
    Let count_b be proc list_count with b
    If count_a is not equal to count_b:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count_a:
        Let instr_a be proc list_at with a, i
        Let instr_b be proc list_at with b, i
        Let match be proc instructions_equal with instr_a, instr_b
        If match is not equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Two parameter streams are equal when they have the same length and the same name
plus the same value type at every position.
@End Reasoning
Process called "param_streams_equal" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    Let count_a be proc list_count with a
    Let count_b be proc list_count with b
    If count_a is not equal to count_b:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count_a:
        Let pa be proc list_at with a, i
        Let pb be proc list_at with b, i

        Let name_a be proc dict_get with pa, "name"
        Let name_b be proc dict_get with pb, "name"
        Let names_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with name_a, name_b
        If names_match is not equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If

        Let type_a be proc dict_get with pa, "param_type"
        Let type_b be proc dict_get with pb, "param_type"
        Let types_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with type_a, type_b
        If types_match is not equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Two result streams are equal when they have the same length and the same result
value type at every position.
@End Reasoning
Process called "result_streams_equal" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    Let count_a be proc list_count with a
    Let count_b be proc list_count with b
    If count_a is not equal to count_b:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count_a:
        Let ra be proc list_at with a, i
        Let rb be proc list_at with b, i
        Let type_a be proc dict_get with ra, "result_type"
        Let type_b be proc dict_get with rb, "result_type"
        Let types_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with type_a, type_b
        If types_match is not equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Two function streams are equal when they have the same length and, at every
position, the same name and structurally equal parameter / result / body streams.
This is the load-bearing whole-function round-trip check.
@End Reasoning
Process called "function_streams_equal" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    Let count_a be proc list_count with a
    Let count_b be proc list_count with b
    If count_a is not equal to count_b:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count_a:
        Let fa be proc list_at with a, i
        Let fb be proc list_at with b, i

        Let name_a be proc dict_get with fa, "name"
        Let name_b be proc dict_get with fb, "name"
        Let names_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with name_a, name_b
        If names_match is not equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If

        Let params_a be proc dict_get with fa, "parameters"
        Let params_b be proc dict_get with fb, "parameters"
        Let params_match be proc param_streams_equal with params_a, params_b
        If params_match is not equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If

        Let results_a be proc dict_get with fa, "results"
        Let results_b be proc dict_get with fb, "results"
        Let results_match be proc result_streams_equal with results_a, results_b
        If results_match is not equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If

        Let body_a be proc dict_get with fa, "body"
        Let body_b be proc dict_get with fb, "body"
        Let body_match be proc body_streams_equal with body_a, body_b
        If body_match is not equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Two export streams are equal when they have the same length and the same public
name plus internal reference at every position.
@End Reasoning
Process called "export_streams_equal" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    Let count_a be proc list_count with a
    Let count_b be proc list_count with b
    If count_a is not equal to count_b:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count_a:
        Let ea be proc list_at with a, i
        Let eb be proc list_at with b, i

        Let name_a be proc dict_get with ea, "name"
        Let name_b be proc dict_get with eb, "name"
        Let names_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with name_a, name_b
        If names_match is not equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If

        Let int_a be proc dict_get with ea, "internal_name"
        Let int_b be proc dict_get with eb, "internal_name"
        Let ints_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with int_a, int_b
        If ints_match is not equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Probe entry point
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "main" returns Integer:
    Let results be proc create_test_results from TestUtils
    proc begin_suite from TestUtils with results, "WebAssembly (WAT) translation round-trip"

    Note:
    Representative WAT snippet. Newlines are explicit \n in the Runa string
    literal. The instruction heads (i32.add / local.get) are not keywords, so the
    lexer classifies them as instruction mnemonics and the parser tags them
    WASM_INSTRUCTION; the structural keywords (func / param / result / export)
    drive the WasmNode classification in classify_head.
    :End Note
    Let source be "(module\n  (func $add (param $a i32) (param $b i32) (result i32)\n    (i32.add (local.get $a) (local.get $b)))\n  (export \"add\" (func $add)))\n"

    Note: --- Stage 1: source -> HIR ---
    Let hir1 be proc wasm_source_to_hir with source
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "pipeline produced HIR dictionary", hir1

    Let type_value be proc dict_get with hir1, "type"
    Let type_is_wasm be proc string_equals from StringCore with type_value, "wasm_module"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "HIR type is wasm_module", type_is_wasm, 1

    Let functions1 be proc dict_get with hir1, "functions"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "HIR carries a functions section", functions1
    Let func_count1 be proc list_count with functions1
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "1 function parsed", func_count1, 1

    Let exports1 be proc dict_get with hir1, "exports"
    Let export_count1 be proc list_count with exports1
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "1 export parsed", export_count1, 1

    Note: --- Stage 1 content: function $add signature ---
    Let func0 be proc list_at with functions1, 0
    Let func0_name be proc dict_get with func0, "name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "function name is '$add'", func0_name, "$add"

    Let params1 be proc dict_get with func0, "parameters"
    Let param_count1 be proc list_count with params1
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "function has 2 parameters", param_count1, 2

    Let param0 be proc list_at with params1, 0
    Let param0_name be proc dict_get with param0, "name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "param[0] name is '$a'", param0_name, "$a"
    Let param0_type be proc dict_get with param0, "param_type"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "param[0] type is 'i32'", param0_type, "i32"

    Let param1 be proc list_at with params1, 1
    Let param1_name be proc dict_get with param1, "name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "param[1] name is '$b'", param1_name, "$b"
    Let param1_type be proc dict_get with param1, "param_type"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "param[1] type is 'i32'", param1_type, "i32"

    Let results_list1 be proc dict_get with func0, "results"
    Let result_count1 be proc list_count with results_list1
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "function has 1 result", result_count1, 1
    Let result0 be proc list_at with results_list1, 0
    Let result0_type be proc dict_get with result0, "result_type"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "result type is 'i32'", result0_type, "i32"

    Note: --- Stage 1 content: folded body instruction (i32.add (local.get $a) (local.get $b)) ---
    Let body1 be proc dict_get with func0, "body"
    Let body_count1 be proc list_count with body1
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "function body has 1 top-level instruction", body_count1, 1

    Let add_instr be proc list_at with body1, 0
    Let add_opcode be proc dict_get with add_instr, "opcode"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "body opcode is 'i32.add'", add_opcode, "i32.add"

    Let add_ops be proc dict_get with add_instr, "operands"
    Let add_opc be proc list_count with add_ops
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "i32.add has 2 operands", add_opc, 2

    Let nested0 be proc list_at with add_ops, 0
    Let nested0_type be proc dict_get with nested0, "type"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "operand[0] is a nested instruction", nested0_type, "instruction"
    Let nested0_op be proc dict_get with nested0, "opcode"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "operand[0] opcode is 'local.get'", nested0_op, "local.get"
    Let nested0_args be proc dict_get with nested0, "operands"
    Let nested0_arg0 be proc list_at with nested0_args, 0
    Let nested0_arg0_val be proc dict_get with nested0_arg0, "value"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "operand[0] immediate is '$a'", nested0_arg0_val, "$a"

    Let nested1 be proc list_at with add_ops, 1
    Let nested1_op be proc dict_get with nested1, "opcode"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "operand[1] opcode is 'local.get'", nested1_op, "local.get"
    Let nested1_args be proc dict_get with nested1, "operands"
    Let nested1_arg0 be proc list_at with nested1_args, 0
    Let nested1_arg0_val be proc dict_get with nested1_arg0, "value"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "operand[1] immediate is '$b'", nested1_arg0_val, "$b"

    Note: --- Stage 1 content: export "add" -> $add ---
    Let export0 be proc list_at with exports1, 0
    Let export0_name be proc dict_get with export0, "name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "export name is 'add'", export0_name, "add"
    Let export0_internal be proc dict_get with export0, "internal_name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "export internal name is '$add'", export0_internal, "$add"

    Note: --- Stage 2: HIR -> WAT text ---
    Let emitted be proc generate_wasm_from_hir from WasmBackend with hir1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "backend produced WAT text", emitted
    Let emitted_len be proc string_length from StringCore with emitted
    proc assert_greater_than from TestUtils with results, "emitted WAT is non-empty", emitted_len, 0

    Note: --- Stage 3: re-parse the emitted text -> HIR (the SECOND emission),
    Note: then assert the section streams are structurally equal. This is the
    Note: load-bearing round-trip assertion. ---
    Let hir2 be proc wasm_source_to_hir with emitted
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "re-parse of emitted WAT produced HIR", hir2

    Let type_value2 be proc dict_get with hir2, "type"
    Let type_is_wasm2 be proc string_equals from StringCore with type_value2, "wasm_module"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "re-parsed HIR type is wasm_module", type_is_wasm2, 1

    Let functions2 be proc dict_get with hir2, "functions"
    Let func_count2 be proc list_count with functions2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "re-parsed preserves 1 function", func_count2, 1

    Let exports2 be proc dict_get with hir2, "exports"
    Let export_count2 be proc list_count with exports2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "re-parsed preserves 1 export", export_count2, 1

    Note: Spot-check survival on the SECOND emission directly (not just stage 1).
    Let r_func0 be proc list_at with functions2, 0
    Let r_func0_name be proc dict_get with r_func0, "name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip function name survives", r_func0_name, "$add"

    Let r_body be proc dict_get with r_func0, "body"
    Let r_add_instr be proc list_at with r_body, 0
    Let r_add_opcode be proc dict_get with r_add_instr, "opcode"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip body opcode survives", r_add_opcode, "i32.add"

    Let r_export0 be proc list_at with exports2, 0
    Let r_export0_name be proc dict_get with r_export0, "name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip export name survives", r_export0_name, "add"

    Note: --- Full structural equality across functions and exports ---
    Let funcs_equal be proc function_streams_equal with functions1, functions2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip functions structurally equal", funcs_equal, 1

    Let exports_equal be proc export_streams_equal with exports1, exports2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip exports structurally equal", exports_equal, 1

    proc print_summary from TestUtils with results
    Let failed be proc get_failed from TestUtils with results
    proc destroy_test_results from TestUtils with results

    Return failed
End Process
